data.content:
Yes! For simple inline data, use `[DataRow]` — it's simpler and strongly typed at the call site:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

If you need complex objects that can't be compile-time constants, keep `DynamicData` but use tuples or a typed wrapper to avoid `object[]` downcasting:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)[]> TestData =>
[
    [("valid@email.com", true)],
    [("invalid", false)],
];
```

**TL;DR:** Prefer `[DataRow]` for primitive/const values. Reserve `DynamicData` for cases where test data requires runtime construction.
